Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the release of the former minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic offences in second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signing of an agreement with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine over the purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not yet final and the appeals court has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 of the Penal Code condemning the former Prime Minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for approval.
