IBM History: From the Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York one hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 – it was originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It owned inventions such as the famous "signer clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over its supervisory board.
Flint signed the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him manage the company.
The new leader overshadowed IBM’s founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are built).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson ran the company, turnover doubled by $9 million and the company’s great expansion began across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM personnel and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the computer standard of that time, came on the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer comprehensive advice and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not improved, for example, with regard to transport and city administration.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team working with voice recognition.
