How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five state-authorized travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time sold in most cases trips only to the socialist bloc, because travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, afterwards the Yugoslav regime leaned westwards and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies in those times also offered trips to the West, but one had to stand in line with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The Czech way of travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the currently favorite destination, Croatia, could not travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, the visa waiver for travel to neighbouring states in Western Europe was imposed, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovakia, for a long time, were not tired of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take food with them (conserves, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it also average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in demand for travel.
With increasing demand for travel agencies began, starting in 1997, to regularly prepare trips using charter flight connections, which caused travel prices to drop incredibly compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining passenger volume discounts.
By the late 1990s, Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost every developed country except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and hot countries. This winter will already be flying directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they have spent more than 15,000 CZK per head on travel abroad, including on-site expenses.
