It contains some notable names, important treatises or famous battles; there are virtually no ambassadors, elegant journalists or discussions about tactics or material.
It’s not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as “a book about how it happened.” It’s about “feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods.”
"The beauty and pain of battle" combines the wartime experiences of about 20 ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and administrators.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Some will become prisoners of war, or lose their members, go mad, or die.
Their lives flash here like votive candles lit in a church; some new ones are added to the mix while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund’s book is a deviation from standard history books.
It is also a correction to the notion that World War I was only the fatal trench war on the Western front.
"The Beauty and Pain of Battle" expertly moves through other war theatres: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book fall over the hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the tse-tse flies are an intractable problem.
This is a moving book, almost from the beginning.
The war floods the lives of these people as a natural catastrophe, a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When the artillery fire is heard in the distance, and you are a woman who is at home with your children, do you stay or run away?
Anyway, who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is going on, not even why this war has to be fought.
“Lack of facts,” notes Mr. Englund, “has been filled with conjectures, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.”
"The Beauty and Pain of Battle" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian Army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German sailor from the offshore fleet.
His stories have been obtained for the most part from memoirs, letters and other material already published earlier.
The explanations of their lives may be frightening or moving, but they are more full of life in the accumulation of small moments, lost details, of Mr. Englund.
Many of these are about deprivation and dealing with what is there.
About telling the story of a German schoolgirl says, "Substitute everywhere."
"Succession of coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues to talk about the substitute food in Germany.
It describes "meat made from cooked rice and pressed into ram fat (and topped with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made from roots and dried potato peels; shoes with wooden soles".
There are, he notes, "837 permitted meat substitutes in the production of sausages, 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American recognizes his own impulse towards savagery and manifests about war: “You feel that, after all, this is what men are conceived for and not to sit in armchairs with a cigarette and a whiskey, the afternoon newspaper or a best seller, and pretend that that varnish means civilization and that there is no barbarian behind that starchy and stained breast.”
Instead, a British soldier realizes that he will probably die, and that no one will find out or care.
“Once one resigns to the thought of sacrificing oneself, one would like to think that it could happen in front of the public,” he writes.
Instead, it is horribly similar "to a convict being strangled in secret."
Other observations are about an old Europe disappearing, and about new types of terror.
"The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition," writes Mr Englund, "a war between factories."
It reflects the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the young century: the eloquent and ideologically convinced mass killer in fine-fashioned clothes running his butchery while sitting behind a desk."
People behave in unforeseen ways; there is both ignoble and heroic behavior.
Mr. Englund speaks of the soldiers who actively tried to catch a venereal disease of prostitutes as a way of evading service at the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade of gonococcal pus, which soldiers buy and embroider their genitals with in the hope of ending up in the hospital," he writes.
“Those who are truly desperate rub it over their eyes, which often gives rise to lifelong blindness.”
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund’s agile but not extravagant prose is perfectly adapted to his human task.
In dozens of small scenes it reflects the way in which the war has “unleashed exceptionally uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred.”
People begin to ask why their leaders are making them fight.
The best books about World War I have often been indirect, such as The Great War and Paul Fussell's Modern Memory, or novels such as No novelty at the front of Erich María Remarque, rather than comprehensive stories.
The volume of Mr. Englund joins an unconventional pantheon.
His book has one of the most devastating endings I can remember in a non-fiction work.
I won't reveal it.
But it is as if he had come from his book, torn that page of dramatis personae out of your fingers, and burned it with a match.
