Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having carried out a killing in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time preceding his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to reach them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British study center DEMOS.
Facebook’s stash of personal information is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine its desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have been using it for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million right-wing group fans across Europe and then directed ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
“It’s a whole new way to do an investigation,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not at all surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry at immigration.
“Those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health problems to social trends as expressed in “likes”, messages on walls, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom, pushing the number of academic papers with the site’s name in the title to nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach with a folder on the street.
“Before, when you tried to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You’d have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunkenness feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that students’ peers, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student post too many status updates with their drunkenness.
“You can’t treat a problem if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Child Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk that would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly “punching” its own population for data.
The Site Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine’s Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed – digital freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make available to others their abundance of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not – the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
“I don’t think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study that carried out with students’ public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it’s impossible to know what part of a user’s profile information and wall messages are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
That’s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a clipboard and pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for entering the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about the social — and a lot of the social still happens offline.”
