7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Missing Interview Shown at Theater This Week
Following the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted as a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of flowcharts - a man who believed many executives suffered "a disease consisting of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds over the dawn of the personal computer, and sat down for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, it had barely been 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working heavily on his new computer company NeXT, awaiting popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used on Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during its transport.
It was only after Jobs's death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly re-edited, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Missing 68-Minute Interview, which hits Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and the answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward the most important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic about The Missing Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it was and it did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Missing Interview:
About how you learned to run a business:
“Throughout the years in the business, I always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers that you invariably get are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Disconcerted by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made with a good eye, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that assured that they could determine commercial costs in detail.
The Joke to the Pope:
Jobs recounts the "Blue Box" he built himself with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been written extensively about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and you were screaming through the public phone and coming back a minute later to the public phone next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke he and Wozniak nearly abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the U.S. diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go and answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Soon after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a summer part-time job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for her.
Improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... I was screaming that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went outside and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and it was totally reliable.
About big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s revival, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble upon his vision, and lose control of their market share.
“Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, and what?”
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no longer successful.
The sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up leading the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make the electrons do, the glass does them, the robots do them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all boils down to taste – it boils down to trying to expose you to the best a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been embarrassed about stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were accidentally the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dine with healthcare law rivals while court accepts case
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically controversial question of whether they would accept the challenge to President Obama’s healthcare law, two of his magistrates, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were treated to a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will expose the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states defying the total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a cry of war for conservative activists across the country.
The judges agreed to admit the lawsuit, and in fact a historic five-and-a-half-hour allegation is expected by March, and the result is likely to further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court’s decision becomes known.
The attorney who will appear in court and argue that the law must be discarded will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the Federalist Society’s annual dinner, a group that has been devoted to defending conservative legal principles for many years.
Another company that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the law-defying trade associations, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel, hours after the court’s preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most prominent Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the healthcare law.
Special guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it is not something that conflicts with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, they could be said to fall under the Canon Code 4C, which says: “A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related and other organizations, although the judge cannot be a speaker, an honorary guest, or feature in the program of such an event.”
However, Scalia and Thomas’ absolute proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with enormous financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This impressive breach of ethics and indifference to the code goes against the lawsuits of several judges that the court adheres to by the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were gayed at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have pending cases before the court."
Their appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say they too easily mix the court’s activity with the agenda driven by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas’ wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is Magistrate Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the Attorney General of the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were presented in the court of first instance.
Her critics have pushed for Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in upholding the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has not given any indication that he will.
