How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging accusations of sexual harassment with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired soccer coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “stacked” with an open microphone asserting U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner ridiculed his denials quickly denied by the irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much cheating do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Many of these lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been refuted.
Liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always stutter, babble, blush or worry.
It cannot be concluded either that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, questioning, and times.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel comfortable, handling their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more "other-oriented lies" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they usually say tend to be "normal").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
It helps provide benchmarks to measure changes afterwards.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally punches their foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when they see their feet punching in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal, and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not as evidence of deception.
Deceiving people can freeze their upper body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview relief” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely show that the interview is over only to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a national search for her.
People who deceive can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... up to what I know... to my mind."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will enhance anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
