Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official entourage, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican peer, Felipe Calderón, the highest point on an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the agenda spread by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "suitable for the exchange of information in all political matters between the two nations," the South American country's presidency posted on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a declaration that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation of its ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group made up of the world’s most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has been in force with the South American country since January this year, an agreement to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to expedite the realization of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), made up of countries that have not implemented all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have in force since 2004 a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) that has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
