Gilberto López Meyer, director general of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Staff operated at cruise speed and that this happened in a soft upward terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations the flight was performed under the visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during flight and terrain.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM placed appropriate conditions for take-off, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico presented layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloud conditions the crew has sought a zone of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar aircraft record match, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The aircraft’s debris dispersion pattern allows us to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident there is still no evidence revealed in the remains of the ship of some kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the field.
During fieldwork, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the terrain presents a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disjointed along that path.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After the thorough search in a wider area than the cordoned site, around the crash, no dispersed parts of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity' protocol, which will allow markers associated with overweight to be counted.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate, whether or not they are entitled, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests for minors are carried out, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Mexico State Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Mexico State East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 children is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and youth to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
At World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he said the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific dietary questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and hereditary family history of diseases, with the purpose of avoiding risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
On Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetics (seeking to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) are applied to all participants.
Cruz Lopez noted that this research owes to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic increase," the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
On average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indian American, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which allows to detect if they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood that he will suffer from metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors give it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV for most of the day, and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (sizes, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics that is analyzed in this protocol.
