Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were answered, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a full-fledged researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who said that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement were to be reduced, they could be removed.
A technological opinion of the bumps, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge of it develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and thus the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is changing during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt binder, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By moving the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to diffuse very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt binder, abundant, is placed a last layer called rolling binder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt bin and provide friction along the way.
As it is the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the stresses, the rolling pad also requires to have the proper thickness and the material from which it is made should be taken care.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt bin.
When the ground is moistened, the water diffuses inside the folder and it is difficult to come out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear out is the rolling film and only then the asphalt binder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Investigators explained that vehicle loading is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the pavement layers should always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is complied with, to prevent bumps forming frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to be researched and worked on the asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair the bumps with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
