The Occupy Wall Street movement on Tuesday challenged New York authorities by trying to re-enter, under a court order, Manhattan Square from where they were evicted early in the morning and by trying to occupy another Big Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were crowded in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a court order that allows the “outraged” to return to camp in the place, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
“Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to re-camp in the square, we will settle down somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ups and demonstrations,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray said the “outraged” response to the eviction of his camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting forced evacuation from the site and allowing protesters to stay camped.
In addition, the "outraged" proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and owned by the Trinity Church parish.
