Some of the protesters displaced there were carrying and distributing copies of that court order at this time and even handing them over to the agents guarding the square, which provoked "some small clashes," Bray said, who denounced that some officers had beaten the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting members of Occupy Wall Street or enforcing “laws that were published after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with stores or other properties they previously used.”
Mayor Bloomberg told reporters that because of the court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and to protesters, who he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to resettle with tents and sleeping bags.
The governor personally defended the early morning eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which about 200 arrests were carried out and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "a place where people would not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, harm other people," because "some businesses would have received threats" and neighbors would fear "for their quality of life."
“This morning’s eviction was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is deeply more interested in preserving financial interests than those of U.S. workers,” the movement’s spokesman added, accusing the mayor of “lacking respect for freedom of expression.”
Occupy Wall Street officials also said they plan to hold “great actions” for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions, to commemorate the two-month-long protests, which began Sept. 17.
