Japan Reborn After Earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescent by the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe the country has suffered since World War II.
Early estimates by the Government of Tokyo amounted to $300 billion in material losses, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have been mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data of Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to pass page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the fastest pace of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the upturn in the purchase of machinery to restore the areas ravaged by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% fall in capital expenditures that was observed from January to March, the first setback after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real revolt of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of crises to strengthen – or rebuild – infrastructures, to use the shortfalls to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, in particular, thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan’s GDP.
This variable escalated by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "safe haven values" chosen by investors fleeing the euro zone debt crisis and the cloudy U.S. forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slab on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products become more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic flotation line is determined by the health of large tech groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September on the yen price.
While markets continue to besiege the EU’s peripheral countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower its guard.
“We need to be aware of the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand’s floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy.
And, indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said most member countries showed stronger signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator anticipating tipping points in the global economy highlighted that major powers are slowing down.
It dropped four-tenths to 100.4 points, up from August’s 100.8.
The euro area even fell below the 100-level average, with eight-tenths down to 99.13 points.
