Greece will need a new adjustment plan to straighten its economy.
This is what Prime Minister Lucas Papadémos declared to Parliament on Monday, November 14; he added that the 100 days granted to his Union Government would not be enough to achieve this goal.
"To make efforts that lead to the recovery of the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new budget adjustment programme," said the head of government, who delivered his first public address during the opening debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken during the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "primary task" of the new government, since "the country's permanence in the euro area" is at stake, he added.
Accordingly, Papadémos has predicted that the country's public deficit will be reduced "to about 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after reaching 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
The right rejects further austerity measures
Antonis Samaras, the head of the right-wing group, on Monday showed his support for the measures already approved to try to get out of the debt crisis, but has warned that his party will not commit to additional austerity measures.
"We will not vote in favour of new measures," he said during a meeting with members of his New Democracy party.
He noted that he agreed with the targets of deficit and debt reduction, as well as the fight against waste, but against any policy that prevents economic recovery.
To Olli Rehn, European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs, who warned that the IMF and the EU would not unlock the necessary €8 billion loan without a written guarantee of all parties’ support for the planned measures, Antonio Samaras replied that his word would be sufficient and that he would not sign anything because of external pressure.
Expert Committee Says Euthanasia and Assisted Suicide Must Be Legalized
Canadians live denying death, Royal Society of Canada report says
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cases of cancer.
Canadian society denies death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they wish to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient considers such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
For starters, experts cite a recent poll by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Québec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report came to conclusions that did not agree with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are incompetent or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
“In Canada, euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal.”
“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal,” explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Remember that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favor of euthanasia, since they believe it would allow people whose death is about to alleviate their suffering, according to a survey by Angus Reid in 2010.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
As for people who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
With regard to the maintenance or discontinuation of health care for a patient, the situation is not as clear, according to the authors of the report.
In addition, among its recommendations, it is suggested that it should be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of health care, if legally refused, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also requests that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses end-of-life care without fear of facing a complaint.
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cases of cancer.
Finally, in relation to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered as euthanasia and undergo the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of the experts signing the report as "extreme", inter alia because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 years of age can ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that “in society, there are labels and limitations.”
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed “strong opposition” to the report’s findings, calling it a “manifesto in favor of euthanasia.”
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, calls into question especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
Jordanian king urges Assad to step down
Damascus denounces “conspiracy”
Syria is increasingly isolated
Partisans of Bashar al-Assad demonstrated yesterday in front of the building of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
Yesterday, diplomatic pressure on Syria was intensified by Bashar al-Assad, who, with the support of Russia, resists it and denounces that there is a “conspiracy” against the country.
Two days after the suspension of Syria by the Arab League, the European Union has tightened sanctions against Damascus, while Turkey and Jordan, neighbors of Syria, have spoken out in favour of President Assad’s abandonment of power.
King Abdullah II of Jordan was the first Arab leader to ask President Bashar al-Assad to “give up power” in Syria, where a quarantine of civilians and members of the regime’s forces have already died.
"If Bashar really cares about his country, he should resign, in addition to creating the necessary conditions for a new phase of Syrian political life," the king of Jordan, neighboring Syria, said in an interview with the BBC.
The head of Turkish diplomacy, Ahmet Davutoglu, has regretted that the mediation efforts Turkey has been making since the beginning of the year with the Syrian regime have ended in failure.
“Those who are not at peace in the Middle East with their peoples and cannot satisfy them will leave,” he said, referring to Syria, a neighboring country with which Turkey is taking an increasingly harsh stance.
Following the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union, the United States has welcomed the “strengthening of the consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime”.
“The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League and other countries, such as Turkey, are taking on an increasingly harsh tone” regarding the crackdown in Syria, said Mark Toner, a spokesman for the State Department.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime’s forces have already been killed in the Deraa region of southern Syria, the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSHR) has announced.
Two other civilians have died "during bombardments and heavy machine gun shootings in Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
During a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Al Mualem said the country was “moving towards the end of the crisis.”
In addition, it has reacted firmly to the decision of the Arab League to suspend Damascus from his duties, which in his opinion constitutes "a dangerous step".
