A Russian scientist has collaborated with the Iranian nuclear program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has collaborated with Iran on the development of a detonator that can be used with a nuclear weapon, an American NGO specializing in atomic risk said on Monday.
For the researcher’s identification, the Institute of Science and International Security (ISIS) is based on a recent report from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and other documents issued by that UN agency.
The IAEA last week expressed its "serious concern" over a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear program.
According to ISIS, based extensively on IAEA documents, Danilenko, born in 1934, would have worked for three decades, since the 1960s, at a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk, Ural, and would have participated in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, it would have left the center to form a company focused on the production of "nanodiamonds" in Kiev.
The economic problems of his company would have led him to contact, in 1995, the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine.
He is believed to have cooperated with the Iranian program between 1996 and 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA mentions that there are “clear indications that Iran is developing” a nuclear detonation system “with the help of a foreign expert, who not only knew the technique well, but also, as one member state has reported to the Agency, worked for most of his career in such technology in the military nuclear program of his home country.”
Crimes and crimes against Muslims have increased by 50%
Crimes and crimes against Muslims have increased by nearly 50% between 2009 and 2010, while, over the same period, the remaining types of racial and religious violence have decreased or increased only slightly, according to statistics released by the FBI on Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of acts of violence committed against Muslims has increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, i.e. it has increased by 49 per cent, compared with a 13 per cent increase in acts of violence against Catholics, a 4 per cent reduction in crimes against Jews and an overall 14 per cent increase in the number of crimes and anti-religious crimes.
The total number of “hate crimes” has grown slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3 percent are due to racial differences and 20 percent to religious differences, according to the FBI.
“After a decline in 2009, it is worrying that such crimes and crimes have again escalated,” Human Rights First said, “the increase in acts of violence against Muslims is particularly significant,” the organization said in a statement.
“Human Rights First has long pointed out that violence against Muslims, as well as all kinds of hate crimes, should be considered a serious violation of human rights,” said Paul Legendre, an official at the organization.
“The U.S. government can and should endeavour to end such abuses,” he adds, considering that such efforts could include an improvement in police reports of “hate crimes.”
The “hate crime” in U.S. federal law was inherited from the era of the civil rights struggle.
Such legislation was adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish acts of violence linked to race, skin color, religion, origin and, now, sexual inclination.
