Austrian
Introducing a “golden rule” in the Constitution
The ruling Austrian Social-Democratic/Christian-Democratic government decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a "golden rule" budget to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible degradation of Austria's sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure far above the ceiling of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were reduced to a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay €3 billion more in interest each year,” said Deputy Democrat Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to the euro area member countries on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a Law of equivalent value.
The system adopted by the Austrian government is close to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural government deficit should decrease by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, from 2017, the federal state’s structural government deficit should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is to reduce public debt by 2020/2021 under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
A strong yen
Noda threatens new foreign exchange market intervention
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese authorities would intervene again to mark the change if the yen continued to rise.
"We will intervene, as we did last time, if we find that there is excessive volatility" in the yen exchange rate, Noda told the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen rose to levels close to the record highs produced by the intervention of the Japanese authorities on October 31.
That day, Tokyo massively sold yen for dollars to lower the value of the Japanese currency, which had just reached a new record since 1945 compared to the U.S. currency.
But the yen has been rising steadily since then, driven by investor purchases that see it as a “safe haven value” in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar traded again on Tuesday at less than 77 yen and the euro has fallen below the symbolic bar of 105 yen, reaching levels close to those triggered by the last intervention.
Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was trading at around 120 yen and the euro at over 160 yen.
This explosion of the Japanese currency harms the exports of the archipelago, since it increases the price of Made in Japan products and reduces the value of the revenues obtained abroad by Japanese companies when they convert them to the national currency.
"Japan is struggling to rebuild itself" after the March 11 earthquake and tsunami, which devastated the northeastern Tohoku region, said Noda, who fears that the yen's rising price will cut the weak recovery.
The world’s third-largest economic powerhouse has recovered growth in the third quarter (1.5% compared to the previous quarter), for the first time in a year, thanks to an increase in exports and consumption of households affected by the catastrophe.
But the Prime Minister considers that the high level of the yen did not reflect "Japan's economic bases."
Finance Minister Jun Azumi has called on the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
However, the institution’s deputy governor, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken “appropriate measures,” implying that further monetary flexibility should not be expected on Wednesday.
During its last meeting at the end of October, the issuing institute increased its purchases of Treasury Letters by five trillion yen (€47 billion), bringing to the 55 trillion yen (€519 billion) threshold of funds it devotes to the acquisition of various financial securities to flood the liquidity market.
