Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas.
If there is one issue that cannot be addressed with short-term considerations or simply emotions in mind, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting be a time to reflect on these issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The discussion will be useful only if it considers the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources will have to be alleviated to continue to produce electricity continuously, not to mention the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case either in Belgium, which places its own under the necessity of finding a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which aims solely at building state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming construction of a power plant interrupted after the crash of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a discourse.
The Berlin election will mean an increase in the price of electricity, a greater dependence on energy due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal power plants.
In a few months, the detrimental effects will be noticed.
The case of Denmark must be meditated.
European champion in the wind sector, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistent nature of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear power would imply a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would diminish realism to the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express principled opposition to this type of energy, according to surveys.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has lost its ability to build an industrial sector with 125,000 managerial jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and which can create non-deflectable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of those SMEs and the loss of 6 billion euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not have consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to these progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While all the electric actors who want to build a plant are studying it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for Areva and EDF competitors, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the figures policy, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Interior Minister (see the May 23 Libération newspaper) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and right shared fears of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande limits himself to including banality, indicating that co-development will solve the “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, is perhaps profitable electorally, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in immigrant countries.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that immigrants can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pushing for lower wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are primarily engaged in occupations in sectors where there is a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country lacking anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of nationals to have a positive impact on national wages and employment.
In light of the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that an increase of 1% in migration flows represents a rise in real wages in the long term of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average throughout his or her lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which dissuaded immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this since, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that for democracy to triumph over its enemies, it would suffice to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little One", that this was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an “instrument of oppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot used to say.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected on in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now been displaced and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and disorderly.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a halt to the void of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take blows of effect, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time on a European scale.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that falls under the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, the one that suffers from its helplessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers a humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investment.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it leads to disaster.
Having fought against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors for a long time, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But to think of it without further political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new impasse.
We must take a new stage in European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
Interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson remains applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let’s make it European.
Cards with "contactless" chip are generalized
The world chip card show kicks off on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, the year 2011 is expected to end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, phones with SIM cards, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart cabinet.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for joint transport or purchases simply by bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share is expected to continue to increase in 2012 (estimated 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the world market for chip cards (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payments sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
To get the upper gear, however, it is necessary for the banks to make them available to their customers.
“There are two major French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminating contactless bank cards to their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks Test Mobile Payment
But it is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is indispensable for transactions.
"They're slowing down."
“But I should finally experience a real boom next year.”
“We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units worldwide in 2012,” explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the lead.
The bank Crédit agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and partners will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale also said yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that will allow its customers to pay contactless through their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the long suspected Nigerian Boko Haram sect have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers “already has certainty.”
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show they are cooperating," he said, without giving further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the runways.
Kidnapped at a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the following day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the debris of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The study of the calls made points to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers particularly caught the interest of investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a northern Nigerian city, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
“This is progress, but we must certainly wait to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex suicide bombers or explosive devices in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group as a community of illuminated people not worthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin") incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for Sharia law, while its militants launch into the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are oriented primarily to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks on police stations increased.
Abuya’s reaction was, as usual, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 people were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested while alive, is sentenced to death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern feuds.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that caused 80 deaths in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram re-attacked Abuya, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes its first international target.
The establishment of a terrorist axis in Africa, ranging from Mauritania to Somalia and Nigeria, is a concern for all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to “share all the information.”
