The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and her Netherlands counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe every year through a first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline is expected to be completed by the end of 2012 to supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, it is already talked about the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the Europe of energy, given that the project has created a gap between East and West Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that connects us organically,” Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which major contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to take extreme measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but those responsible for the project renounced it as they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to settle permanently at sea off their shores.
"In case of a breakdown, we will stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have predicted junctions that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, carried by a vessel, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, in charge of building and operating the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transmission capacity to the company for a renewable period of twenty-five years.
“Gazprom will pay for the full capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the project is expected to reach €7.4 billion for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenses.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, with a height of 4.5 meters, form the exit gate of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people a taste for writing back.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged over time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted an old and forgotten object to today's taste, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far away is the confidential production of the early years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a leopard tapas notebook on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled doubles the average rate: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
“No,” says Eric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
“However, there is still a lot to be done.”
It should be noted that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous barriers to accessing employment.
They usually have an older age: 37% are over 50 years old (on average 17%).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% have not finished high school and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In other words, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the heart of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entrepreneur for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest figures available, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We now reach around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees, compared with 82 per cent of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
